
  <sn><md>### How soil quality can be assessed 

The **United States Department of Agriculture (USDA)** has developed a `soil quality test kit` that can be used to `assess soil quality` in the field. The test is designed specifically so that different soils or `different experimental treatments can be compared`. The test includes the following measurements:

| Indicator                        | What it Measures                                                                         | What it Indicates                                                                                               |
| -------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Soil respiration**             | Amount of `CO₂` released from the soil                                                     | Biological activity of the soil                                                                                 |
| **Infiltration**                 | How fast water can infiltrate into the soil                                              | Soil physical condition                                                                                         |
| **Bulk density**                 | Mass of soil solids per unit volume of total soil                                        | How well plant seedlings can emerge and how well air can circulate through the soil                             |
| **Electrical conductivity (EC)** | How well an electrical current travels through the soil water                            | Amount of salt present in the soil                                                                              |
| **pH**                           | Activity of hydrogen ions in soil water                                                  | Whether the soil is acidic, neutral, or basic                                                                   |
| **Nitrate**                      | Amount of nitrate available in the soil                                                  | Availability of the essential plant nutrient nitrogen                                                           |
| **Aggregate stability**          | Extent to which soil aggregates resist falling apart when wetted and struck by raindrops | How well water infiltrates during rainfall or irrigation, and the soil's resistance to erosion by water or wind |
| **Earthworm counts**             | Number of earthworms in the soil                                                         | Soil fertility and improvement of soil physical properties                                                      |
| **Penetration resistance (PR)**  | Resistance encountered by roots while growing through the soil                           | Degree of soil compaction, ease of root growth, and potential impact on crop yield                              |
</md></sn>
